THE RISK:
{
 "id": "enterprise-share-is-stock-not-spend",
 "title": "Enterprise 0.29 is a capacity stock, not PDU spend: a declining, refresh-lagged slice inflates nearly a third of TAM",
 "narrative": "seg.enterprise carries 29% of the market because Synergy says enterprise on-prem holds 32% of global CAPACITY. But rack-PDU revenue follows flows — new builds and refresh — not standing stock. Enterprise on-prem is the one segment in structural decline (56% in 2018 → 32% now → 19% by 2031, minus two points a year): near-zero new-build demand, refresh cycles stretched as workloads migrate out, and the node's own provenance admits refresh demand 'may lag capacity share'. Meanwhile the geo axis never measured enterprise at all (colo denominator), so this slice is doubly unobserved. A third of the TAM is priced off the one number — stock share — that is least predictive of what an entrant can invoice.",
 "category": "fact",
 "targetNodes": [
  "seg.enterprise"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "Enterprise on-prem capacity share is in documented structural decline: 56% (2018) → 32% (end-2025) → 19% (2031), falling ~2pp per year",
   "refs": [
    "digest:seg-mix#c2",
    "digest:seg-mix#c5",
    "digest:seg-mix#c22"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "PDU purchases track capacity flows, not stock: a shrinking installed base generates minimal new-build PDU demand and deferred refresh, so spend share sits well below capacity share — a lag the node's own rationale flags but does not quantify; the GenAI on-prem boost is described only as relief 'after a sustained period of essentially no growth'",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:seg.enterprise",
    "digest:seg-mix#c20"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "seg.enterprise 0.29 overstates the invoiceable enterprise slice of CE rack-PDU demand, and because the geo weights are colo-scoped this overstatement was never exposed to any country-level evidence — the funnel books phantom demand across every geo × enterprise cell",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:seg.enterprise",
    "digest:geo-region-denominator#c0"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The 0.29 is arithmetically clean — Synergy's 32% × the 0.91 carve-out — and the declining trend is right there in the cited excerpt, which makes it feel priced in. It isn't: the model uses the current-year stock share as a spend share, and the decline is exactly why stock overstates spend. The number being visibly sourced hides that it measures the wrong quantity.",
 "expectedObviousness": "medium",
 "falsifier": "Vendor rack-PDU revenue mix (Schneider/Vertiv/Eaton product-line or channel commentary, or an Omdia/IndexBox application split) showing enterprise/on-prem channel revenue at or above ~29% of rack-PDU sales — i.e., spend share tracking capacity share.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.42,
  "rationale": "The stock-vs-flow mismatch is structural and the decline is multi-vintage-consistent, but the GenAI/GPU on-prem build wave (Synergy's own caveat) could temporarily lift enterprise PDU spend above its stock-share trend. [evidence revision: The capacity-share decline (trigger) is firmly corroborated, but the load-bearing stock-vs-flow claim is weakened by Synergy's own clarification that on-prem absolute capacity has been constant and is now being boosted by AI/GPU builds — this undercuts the 'near-zero new-build demand / minimal PDU flow' premise more than the hypothesis credited. No source directly measures enterprise rack-PDU revenue share, so the overstatement cannot be confirmed or falsified. Modest downward adjustment reflects the contradicting caveat while remaining above floor given the structural stock-flow logic is untested.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.45
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "seg.enterprise",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.18,
   "note": "Flow-weighted enterprise share of PDU spend for a declining stock at -2pp/yr with stretched refresh; absolute shrinkage, not a mix-shift, so siblings untouched"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "Enterprise/on-prem share in successive Synergy vintages and any GenAI-driven on-prem build commentary",
   "where": "Synergy Research quarterly capacity-share releases; CRN coverage of the hyperscale-vs-enterprise split",
   "threshold": "On-prem share falling faster than 2pp/yr, or GenAI boost fading from the narrative",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Channel mix for rack power sold into enterprise vs DC operators",
   "where": "Schneider/Eaton/Vertiv earnings-call commentary and distributor (IT-VAR) rack-power sell-through reports",
   "threshold": "Enterprise/IT-channel rack-PDU revenue flat or declining YoY while operator segment grows double-digit",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Obtain one application-split datapoint for rack-PDU revenue by end-user (IndexBox EU report application tables or Omdia vendor/application split) to replace the capacity-as-spend assumption",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "seg.enterprise",
   "note": "A single sourced spend-share resolves the stock-vs-flow gap for a third of TAM"
  },
  {
   "action": "Treat enterprise as a refresh-only opportunity in planning: qualify via IT distributors for retrofit, and exclude enterprise new-build from Year-1 pipeline targets",
   "type": "operational",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": "Aligns sales capacity with the demand that actually flows from a declining stock"
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "contested",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "Hyperscale Operators to Account for 67% of all Data Center Capacity by 2031",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Synergy Research Group",
   "date": null,
   "excerpt": "that leaves enterprise on-premise data centers with just 32% of the total... on-premise will drop to just 19%. After a sustained period of essentially no growth, on-premise data center capacity is receiving something of a boost thanks to GenAI applications and GPU infrastructure.",
   "url": "https://www.srgresearch.com/articles/hyperscale-operators-to-account-for-67-of-all-data-center-capacity-by-2031",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Data Center Market Share Face-Off: Hyperscalers Vs. Colo Vs. Enterprise",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "CRN",
   "date": "2026-04-10",
   "excerpt": "the reason is not that on-premise data center capacity is falling—it had been staying somewhat constant but is now receiving a boost from on-premise deployments of AI and GPU servers. The big change in the picture, of course, is hyperscale operators.",
   "url": "https://www.crn.com/news/data-center/2026/data-center-market-share-face-off-hyperscalers-vs-colocation-vs-enterprise",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Data Center PDU Market Size, Share, Latest Trends & Growth Analysis, 2025-2032",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "MarketsandMarkets",
   "date": null,
   "excerpt": "Data Center PDU Market Size, Share & Trends by ... End User (Hyperscale, Colocation, Enterprise) - Global Forecast to 2032. The rapid growth of hyperscale data centers operated by cloud service providers is driving demand for advanced PDUs.",
   "url": "https://www.marketsandmarkets.com/Market-Reports/data-center-pdu-market-183927907.html",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://www.srgresearch.com/articles/hyperscale-operators-to-account-for-67-of-all-data-center-capacity-by-2031",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "that leaves enterprise on-premise data centers with just 32% of the total. This is in stark contrast to 2018, when 56% of data center capacity was in on-premise facilities. Looking ahead to 2031, hyperscale operators will account for 67% of all capacity, while on-premise will drop to just 19%."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.crn.com/news/data-center/2026/data-center-market-share-face-off-hyperscalers-vs-colocation-vs-enterprise",
   "stance": "contradicts",
   "quote": "the reason is not that on-premise data center capacity is falling—it had been staying somewhat constant but is now receiving a boost from on-premise deployments of AI and GPU servers"
  },
  {
